            <h2>1. Bhimbetka Rock Shelters (Madhya Pradesh)</h2>
            <p>These caves date back over 10,000 years and contain some of the earliest known human artwork in India.</p>
            <p>The paintings depict daily life, hunting scenes, and dancing, created with natural pigments.</p>
            <p>They offer a glimpse into the early development of human civilization and social activities.</p>
            <p>The site is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and a significant archaeological discovery.</p>
            <p>Many paintings are multi-layered, showing different periods of history.</p>
            <p>It is believed that these caves were used as shelters by early humans.</p>
            <p>More than 750 rock shelters have been found in the region.</p>
            <p>Animals such as bison, deer, and elephants are frequently depicted in the cave art.</p>
            <p>Scholars suggest that the caves were continuously occupied from the Stone Age to the Medieval period.</p>
            <p>Some rock formations also resemble animals and figures, adding to their mystery.</p>
            
            <h2>2. Ajanta Caves (Maharashtra)</h2>
            <p>Built between the 2nd century BCE and the 6th century CE, Ajanta is a collection of 30 Buddhist caves.</p>
            <p>The caves are famous for their detailed murals and frescoes depicting the life of Buddha and Jataka tales.</p>
            <p>The paintings are among the finest surviving examples of ancient Indian art.</p>
            <p>They were rediscovered by British officers in the early 19th century.</p>
            <p>The caves also contain beautifully carved stupas and monastic cells.</p>
            <p>They were used as meditation halls and monasteries for Buddhist monks.</p>
            <p>The vibrant colors in the murals were made using natural dyes.</p>
            <p>Intricate sculptures of Buddha and Bodhisattvas adorn the interiors.</p>
            <p>The caves reflect the artistic excellence of both the Maurya and Gupta periods.</p>
            <p>Today, they attract tourists and scholars from around the world.</p>
            
            <h2>3. Ellora Caves (Maharashtra)</h2>
            <p>Constructed between the 6th and 9th centuries CE, Ellora features 34 caves dedicated to Buddhism, Hinduism, and Jainism.</p>
            <p>The site is famous for the Kailasa Temple, a massive monolithic structure carved from a single rock.</p>
            <p>The Hindu caves showcase stunning carvings of deities like Shiva, Vishnu, and Durga.</p>
            <p>Jain caves contain intricate carvings that reflect ascetic principles.</p>
            <p>Buddhist caves include large monasteries and prayer halls.</p>
            <p>The site demonstrates religious harmony and co-existence.</p>
            <p>The craftsmanship of these caves is regarded as a marvel of ancient architecture.</p>
            <p>Some structures have been carved with such precision that they resemble wooden constructions.</p>
            <p>The caves also contain elaborate panels and inscriptions.</p>
            <p>Ellora remains one of the most visited heritage sites in India.</p>
            
            <h2>4. Elephanta Caves (Maharashtra)</h2>
            <p>Located on Elephanta Island, these caves date back to the 5th to 8th centuries CE.</p>
            <p>The most famous sculpture here is the Trimurti, which depicts Lord Shiva in three forms.</p>
            <p>The caves were originally Buddhist but later converted into Hindu shrines.</p>
            <p>The rock-cut temples contain massive pillars and intricate carvings.</p>
            <p>Portuguese colonizers named the island after a large stone elephant found there.</p>
            <p>The caves were heavily damaged by invaders over the centuries.</p>
            <p>Despite the destruction, the artistic mastery of the sculptures remains evident.</p>
            <p>Elephanta is now a UNESCO World Heritage Site.</p>
            <p>The site is accessible by ferry from Mumbai and attracts thousands of visitors annually.</p>
            <p>Today, the caves are preserved as an important cultural and religious site.</p>
